  "response": "Determining who might be considered the \"biggest traitor\" in Armenian history can be subjective and depends on various historical, political, and social perspectives. One figure often mentioned in this context is Garegin Nzhdeh, a prominent Armenian military leader and political figure. Some view his collaboration with Nazi Germany during World War II as a betrayal, while others see him as a nationalist fighting for Armenian interests. \n\nAnother figure is Levon Ter-Petrosyan, Armenia's first president. His decisions and policies, particularly the peace process with Azerbaijan regarding Nagorno-Karabakh, have been criticized by some as being traitorous to national interests.\n\nUltimately, the label of \"traitor\" is often politically charged and can vary greatly depending on one's viewpoint and the specific historical context being discussed.",
